1 c. entities to serve as temporary staging areas,
2 including churches, event centers, and businesses,
3 d. chaplain services,
4 e. first response services, including by medical
5 personnel and honorably discharged veterans,
6 f. transportation services to move people and supplies,
7 and
8 g. other specializations or resources provided by
9 individuals as deemed appropriate for an emergency
10 response.
11 C. At least two county employees designated by the county
12 sheriff, county commissioners, and emergency management personnel
13 shall create, maintain, operate, and update a system that allows
14 county residents to volunteer as members of the Volunteer County
15 Emergency Response Corps, list applicable specialties or available
16 supplies, and share preferred contact information.
17 D. At least once per year, the county sheriff and county
18 commissioners shall hold a public meeting to discuss and promote the
19 Volunteer County Emergency Response Corps. Such meeting may take
20 place in conjunction with any other regularly scheduled public
21 meeting.
22 E. Any volunteer or entity that offers services or supplies
23 pursuant to the Volunteer County Emergency Response Corps shall be
24 immune from liability in a civil action on the basis of any act or
